{"hierarchy":{"paths":[[]]},"sections":[],"kind":"symbol","abstract":[{"text":"A technical demonstration of Embedded Swift running on Playdate by Panic.","type":"text"}],"identifier":{"interfaceLanguage":"swift","url":"doc:\/\/Playdate\/documentation\/Playdate"},"primaryContentSections":[{"kind":"content","content":[{"anchor":"Why-Swift-for-Playdate","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Why Swift for Playdate"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/play.date","type":"reference"},{"type":"text","text":" is a tiny handheld gaming console developed by "},{"isActive":true,"identifier":"https:\/\/panic.com","type":"reference"},{"text":", featuring a Cortex M7 processor and a 400 by 240 1-bit display. Panic provides an SDK for building Playdate games in both C and Lua and is equipped with a Playdate Simulator.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Most Playdate games are traditionally written in Lua for ease of development, but can run into performance problems that necessitate the added complexity of using C.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Embedded Swift solves this problem by pairing high-level ergonomics with low-level performance, while also providing memory safety guarantees that improve productivity and eliminate a common source of bugs."}],"type":"paragraph"},{"anchor":"Get-Started","level":2,"type":"heading","text":"Get Started"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"To build and run the Swift Playdate examples included in this repository, you’ll need some additional tools. Specifically, you need a recent Swift nightly toolchain (built on 3\/7\/24 or later) and a copy of the Playdate SDK. For instructions on setting up your development environment, see "},{"identifier":"doc:\/\/Playdate\/documentation\/Playdate\/DownloadingTheTools","type":"reference","isActive":true},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"inlineContent":[{"type":